issue(id="0019" status="closed")
  title Review bootstrap parallel safety and stale-instance recovery hardening
  user-story
    as-a scrubs maintainer recovering from real bootstrap fallout on long-lived guests
    i-want a clear review of the recent bootstrap hardening changes
    so-that we keep the stability wins, identify the rough edges, and know what still needs follow-up before treating concurrent bootstrap as trustworthy
  premise.
    A real parallel bootstrap batch on July 4, 2026 exposed that
    `bootstrap.nu` was still unsafe under concurrent fresh-instance creation
    and under certain stale running-instance states. Multiple guests inherited
    the wrong host-local SSH listener ports, some hostagents stayed bound to
    old ports even after their instance configs had been refreshed, and a few
    guests reported `Running` while never becoming reachable over host-local
    SSH. Recovery required force-stopping poisoned Lima instances, then
    re-bootstrapping the affected guests one at a time.

    The immediate hardening work changed bootstrap in three important ways.
    First, the host-side rendered Lima template and staged payload moved from
    shared writable paths into per-instance cache paths, removing the most
    direct cross-instance clobbering hazard. Second, bootstrap now refreshes
    running guests when their live SSH listener port or rendered Lima config
    diverges from the intended host-side state. Third, bootstrap now has a
    more aggressive recovery path for stuck shutdowns and for some
    running-but-unreachable SSH states.

    Those changes were strong enough to recover the active canary set. After a
    follow-up repair on July 6, 2026 for the lingering `moview` case, an
    unsandboxed run of `vms/audit-instances.nu` reported `CURRENT` for
    `agents-yaml`, `atom-io`, `celilo`, `lasertag`, `moview`, `puggers`,
    `recoverage`, `redteam`, and `systemd-ts`; `wayforge` remained `STALE`,
    and `tfr` remained `STOPPED`.

    The review question is not whether these changes helped today; they
    clearly did. The question is whether the implementation is now shaped
    correctly for long-term stability, or whether some of the emergency
    recovery behavior should be tightened before scrubs treats parallel
    bootstrap or stale-instance self-healing as a solved problem.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion The review records the current recovered state of the active guest set and distinguishes that operational checkpoint from still-open follow-up work.
    criterion The review explicitly identifies which bootstrap changes are clear keepers, such as per-instance host-side staging and live-config convergence for running guests.
    criterion The review identifies at least one concrete follow-up around stale running-instance detection and at least one around shutdown recovery behavior.
    criterion The review defines what validation is still missing before maintainers should treat concurrent bootstrap as a supported or trusted operator workflow.
  review-items
    item(status="covered").
      The move from shared host-side staging paths to per-instance cache paths
      appears directionally correct and should stay. Rendering
      `lima.local.yaml` and staging `scrubs-bootstrap` under an
      instance-specific cache path removed the clearest race that let parallel
      bootstrap jobs clobber one another's SSH and port-forward metadata.
    item(status="covered").
      Refreshing already-running guests when the live SSH listener port or the
      rendered Lima config diverges from intended state is also a real
      stability improvement and should stay. That convergence logic was
      necessary to recover guests such as `atom-io`, `celilo`, and `redteam`
      in place without delete-and-recreate.
    item(status="covered").
      As of the July 6, 2026 recovery checkpoint, an unsandboxed
      `vms/audit-instances.nu` run reported `CURRENT` for `agents-yaml`,
      `atom-io`, `celilo`, `lasertag`, `moview`, `puggers`, `recoverage`,
      `redteam`, and `systemd-ts`. This demonstrates that the current
      hardening work is strong enough to repair real long-lived guests after
      the observed failure mode, even if the implementation still needs polish.
    item(status="covered").
      The July 6 `moview` incident confirmed that the authoritative fleet
      checkpoint should come from an unsandboxed `vms/audit-instances.nu` run.
      In-sandbox checks could misreport healthy guests as unreachable, while
      the unsandboxed audit correctly reflected that the repaired guest set was
      back to `CURRENT`.
    item(status="covered").
      The SSH recovery path now consults fresh post-start Lima state before it
      retries. If SSH still does not come up after the initial wait window,
      bootstrap reloads the live instance status and `sshLocalPort`, retries
      only for bounded states such as `Running`, `Starting`, or a port mismatch,
      and preserves the final Lima and SSH diagnostics in the raised error.
    item(status="covered").
      The shutdown helper is now narrower and more operator-visible. It still
      uses `limactl stop --force` as an escape hatch, but only after a failed
      ordinary stop leaves the instance stuck in `Running` across a short grace
      window. Other failure classes now surface explicit diagnostics instead of
      collapsing immediately into unconditional force kill.
    item(status="covered").
      Scrubs now has an explicit disposable concurrent validation path in
      `vms/validate-parallel.nu`, with the maintainer wrapper
      `just scrubs-validate-parallel`. The representative batch covers a plain
      guest plus the `moview` and `systemd-ts` shims, and it checks parallel
      bootstrap completion, distinct host SSH listeners, `limactl shell`
      reachability, and host-side `CURRENT` audit health across the batch.
